Package com.geodesk.io.osm

Class OsmPbfReader

java.lang.Object
com.geodesk.io.osm.OsmPbfReader
Direct Known Subclasses:
BaseOsmPbfReader
public class OsmPbfReader extends Object
A base class for reading (and processing) OSM PBF files, which uses a pool of worker threads to maximize throughput. A well-formed OSM PBF file consists of a header block and one or more data blocks. The data blocks contain the OSM features: nodes, ways, and relations. Nodes must appear before ways, ways must appear before relations. (See https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/PBF_Format) Blocks are processed concurrently. The OsmPbfReader processes the three types of feature in phases. This means that all nodes are guaranteed to have been processed before way processing begins; likewise, all ways have been processed by the time relation processing begins. Processing of features happens in the form of events. Subclasses should define a custom WorkerThread class that overrides the event methods of interest: 
     header()
     beginNodes()
     node()
     ndNodes()
     beginWays()
     way()
     endWays()
     beginRelations()
     relation()
     endRelations()
     postProcess()
This custom WorkerThread must be created in the overridden createWorker method: 
     @Override protected WorkerThread createWorker()
     {
         return new MyCustomWorkerThread();
     }
If the WorkerThread instances generate output that must be written sequentially (e.g. by appending to a file), instructions can be passed to a separate output thread by calling output(Runnable). This is more efficient than wrapping such instructions in a synchronized block, as it uses a queue to process Runnable objects. Worker threads may throw exceptions, in which case all threads are interrupted and processing is shut down. Such exceptions are wrapped in an IOException, which is in turn thrown by read(File).

Current limitations

Decoding of single-node messages is not supported, as all major OSM-related software uses the more efficient DenseNodes groups to encode nodes.

    • fail

      protected void fail(Throwable ex)
      Aborts all processing. Interrupts all threads and shuts down. The Throwable argument will be wrapped in an IOException, which will be thrown by the read(File) method.
      Parameters:
      ex - a Throwable indicating the cause of the failure

    • output

      protected void output(Runnable task) throws InterruptedException
      Executes the given Runnable on the output thread, ensuring that such operations happen synchronously. This method can be safely called by the worker threads. It is more efficient than wrapping instructions in a synchronized block, as it uses a blocking queue to hand off tasks to the output thread.
      Parameters:
      task - a Runnable that performs synchronous instructions
      Throws:
      InterruptedException - if interrupted while waiting for space in the output queue
